Bill, Brian:

It is on the face of it odd that stereopsis has not been studied much
in developmentally abnormal monkeys. But there are several good
reasons:

 + studying stereopsis in monkeys is quite difficult; unlike spatial
   tasks -- which they learn quickly and happily -- monkeys seem very
   averse to learning stereo tasks. Some of this may have to do with
   the difficulty of obtaining binocular alignment in haploscopic
   displays (see more below)

 + almost any manipulation that reduces cortical binoculariy affects
   eye alignment. Thus Brian is incorrect when he says that alternate
   occlusion animals are better than strabismics for this test,
   because alternate occlusion causes strabismus. So does monocular
   deprivation, which is useless for this anyway because it is not
   of interest to study stereopsis in an animal that only has one
   functional eye. The result is that failing to find stereopsis is
   a weak result in the absence of objective evidence that the targets
   were actually presented to the appropriate retinal locations. This
   is difficult in cooperative human subjects trained to use Nonius
   markers; it would be all but impossible in monkeys. Thus a negative
   result is almost uninterpretable.

 + the loss of stereopsis is not a particularly important visual
   dysfunction. Amblyopia is a much more serious problem, and much
   more in the NEI's interest.

Now, on the MT/V5 issue, the balance hinges on how you feel about
homology. As Bill knows, I am not a fan of comparative neurology, and
I regard most debates about homology as empty. These debates will
continue, however, and I think it is possible that one day we will
find out that owl monkeys and macaques are not quite the same in their
cortical organization, and that we will have the awkward situation of
having the same name for two different structures. The Vn nomanclature
seems to me agnostic on the issue of hierarchy; it simply says that
this area is the fifth topographic map in the visual pathway, starting
with V1 (for which, I must concede, it's clear that the same name
should be used for all species). It doesn't say it's the fifth rung of
a hierarchical ladder.

					Tony


