In a not very powerful sort of way, yes. No one doubts that binocular
neurons are basic to stereopsis (in the same sense that cones are
basic to vision). Showing that stereopsis goes away when they go away
is sort of trivial (especially when the animal can only see out of one
eye anyway!).

Somewhat better evidence comes from experiments on alternate monocular
occlusion and/or squint, in which stereopsis goes away despite being
able to show that the animal can see with either eye. You can find
references in my old Ann Rev Psych chapter (81), or I'll dig them out
for you if you don't have that to hand. Hirsch did some stuff, so did
Gordon, so did Mitchell.

						T

